  "steps": [
    {
      "id": "intro",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Asking and telling the time",
      "body": "# Telling the time\n\nThe question for the time is always: **¿Qué hora es?** (What time is it?). Note the inverted **¿** at the start of the sentence.\n\nThe answer has one key rule:\n\n- **Es la una** (singular) — only for **one o'clock**.\n- **Son las...** (plural) — for **every other hour**.\n\nExamples:\n\n- *Es la una.* — It's one o'clock.\n- *Son las dos.* — It's two o'clock.\n- *Son las cinco.* — It's five o'clock.\n\nAdd minutes with these building blocks:\n\n- **y media** — half past: *Son las tres y media.* (half past three)\n- **y cuarto** — quarter past: *Son las cuatro y cuarto.* (quarter past four)\n- **menos cuarto** — quarter to: *Son las cinco menos cuarto.* (quarter to five)"
    },
    {
      "id": "step-tageszeit",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Parts of the day",
      "body": "## Morning, afternoon, night\n\nTo say whether it's morning, afternoon or evening, add the part of the day:\n\n- **de la mañana** — in the morning: *Son las ocho de la mañana.* (eight in the morning)\n- **de la tarde** — in the afternoon: *Son las cuatro de la tarde.* (four in the afternoon)\n- **de la noche** — at night: *Son las diez de la noche.* (ten at night)\n\nNote: **mañana** is written with **ñ**."
    },
    {
      "id": "step-reflexive",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Reflexive verbs for routine",
      "body": "## Reflexive verbs\n\nMany daily-routine verbs are **reflexive**. You spot them by the **-se** on the infinitive: *levantarse* (to get up), *ducharse* (to shower), *acostarse* (to go to bed), *despertarse* (to wake up).\n\nReflexive verbs need a pronoun **before** the verb:\n\n| Person | levantarse |\n|---|---|\n| yo | **me** levanto |\n| tú | **te** levantas |\n| él/ella | **se** levanta |\n| nosotros | **nos** levantamos |\n| vosotros | **os** levantáis |\n| ellos/ellas | **se** levantan |\n\nExamples:\n\n- *Me levanto temprano.* — I get up early.\n- *Nos acostamos tarde.* — We go to bed late.\n\nNot every verb is reflexive: **desayunar** (to have breakfast) needs **no** pronoun — *desayuno* (I have breakfast)."
    },
    {
      "id": "step-zusammen",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Putting it together",
      "body": "## Combining time and routine\n\nUse the preposition **a las** (at ... o'clock) to link an activity to a time:\n\n- *Me levanto **a las** siete y desayuno **a las** ocho.* — I get up at seven and have breakfast at eight.\n- *Me acuesto **a las** once de la noche.* — I go to bed at eleven at night.\n\nRemember: for one o'clock it's **a la una** (singular), otherwise **a las** + hour."
    },
